            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Aaron Sharma\u2019s story is not the one his immigrant parents from Punjab envisioned, but it is one he has claimed with quiet pride. Raised in the dense, foggy suburbs of Daly City, Aaron was a ghost in his own life. While his parents worked multiple service jobs to provide for him, their dreams of an engineer or doctor son felt like a language he couldn\u2019t speak. He navigated high school with a constant, low hum of anxiety, graduating with a general diploma and a profound sense of being adrift.\n\nHis early twenties were a blur of dead-end retail jobs, shared rooms in crowded apartments, and a deepening struggle with depression. The city, so full of promise, felt like a wall of glass he couldn't break through. The turning point came at 25, not with a bang, but with a quiet decision to walk into a community health clinic in the Mission District. There, he was connected with a peer supporter\u2014a man only a few years older who spoke of his own past struggles with an honesty that cracked Aaron\u2019s carefully constructed shell. For the first time, Aaron saw a future.\n\nInspired, he pursued a certification to become a Peer Support Specialist. The training gave him the vocabulary for his own experiences and the tools to help others. Now, at 33, he works for a non-profit that partners with local high schools, a role that feels like a karmic full circle. His daily 4.5-mile commute on the 5-Fulton MUNI from his small apartment in the Inner Richmond is a time for reflection. He listens to podcasts, watches the city wake up, and mentally prepares to connect with teenagers who feel as lost as he once did.\n\nAaron\u2019s life is woven into the fabric of San Francisco\u2019s community support network. His partner, Maya, is a case manager he met at a conference. Their evenings are spent cooking, taking long walks through Golden Gate Park, and decompressing from emotionally demanding days. His dreams aren't of wealth, but of impact. He hopes to one day lead a new youth outreach program focused on creative expression. For Aaron, San Francisco is not a city of tech booms, but a city of second chances, a place that allowed him to transform his deepest wounds into a lifeline for others."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the greasy smell of the food court in the Stonestown Galleria, age 22. On his break from folding sweaters, he\u2019d watch families laugh, his own loneliness a physical weight. His parents\u2019 disappointed voices were a constant loop in his head. He felt like a ghost haunting someone else\u2019s vibrant life, a cheap reflection in the mall\u2019s polished floors. It was the moment he realized that just existing wasn't living; it was a quiet despair that would eventually force him to seek help.\n\n2.\nIt wasn't a grand speech that saved him, but four quiet words. He was 25, sitting in a small, stuffy office in the Mission, the air thick with his own shame. The peer supporter, a man with kind eyes, listened to his fractured story and simply said, \"I hear you. I've been there.\" For Aaron, it was like a window being forced open in a room with no air. The validation was so profound, so unexpected, it broke something loose inside him. That day, his future started.\n\n3.\nDuring his peer support certification, age 26, the instructor asked them to share a time they felt hopeless. Aaron's heart hammered. He spoke about the mall food court, his voice barely a whisper at first. But as he described the feeling of being invisible, he saw nodding heads\u2014not pity, but pure understanding. For the first time, his pain wasn't a source of shame, but a point of connection. In that room, his past was reframed from a wound into a map he could use to guide others.\n\n4.\nHe was at Balboa High last year, watching a boy who sat in the back, hoodie up, radiating the same anxiety Aaron knew intimately. Instead of pushing, Aaron just sat nearby during their sessions, talking about his own struggles with feeling lost. After three meetings, the boy finally looked up and said, \"Yeah. That.\" It was a quiet breakthrough, a mirror image of his own past. Riding home on the 5-Fulton, Aaron felt a profound sense of peace. He wasn\u2019t just doing a job; he was closing a circle.\n\n5.\nAt a behavioral health conference downtown, he met Maya. They had both escaped a dense panel on grant writing and were leaning against a railing overlooking Yerba Buena Gardens. She made a dry joke about \"compassion fatigue bingo,\" and he laughed with genuine relief. It wasn't the joke itself, but the shared language underneath\u2014the immediate, unspoken understanding of their emotionally taxing work. In that instant, he didn't feel like a peer supporter or a client, but a person being truly seen by another."
